<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-06-16T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-06-16T00:00:00-05:00" n="581" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d581">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">800.51W89/1149</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">President <persName type="from">Roosevelt</persName>
                                to the Under Secretary of State</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Welles</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-06-16">June 16,
                                1941</date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>I have yours of June 12th in regard to notices of debtor government due
                            dates. As we have already omitted notices to Czechoslovakia and the
                            Baltic States, leaving only France, Hungary, Italy and Rumania, how
                            would it do to send to the French, Hungarian, Italian and Rumanian
                            Ambassadors or Ministers here in Washington a short statement that the
                            notices, due at this time, are not being sent out in the existing
                            circumstances, but that this constitutes, of course, no waiver on the
                            part of the United States Government.</p>
                        <p>What do you think?</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>F[<hi rend="smallcaps">ranklin</hi>] D. R[<hi rend="smallcaps">oosevelt</hi>]</signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>